I think the only elms that grow in Poland are not the same as American elms. The Polish variety is ulmus minor, much smaller than an oak. Our obvious, Polish choice for a stately tree is an oak (and our oak, quercus robur, is different than the American one - it grows more slowly and has different leaves. When new Polish coins were issued in the mid 90s, the designer didn't know this and so our Polish coins feature oak leaves from an American oak, which is considered an invasive species. The irony...).

Over time I learned that if a NYT puzzle inquires about a stately tree, it is an ELM much more often than an oak. Possibly also because American grids are always hungry for more Es? Epees, eels and the like would surely indicate that.

